/-
  PrimitiveRecognitionCalculus/Rigidity/BaseInitiality.lean

  RIGIDITY OF THE δ-BASE (carrier tier: PROVED, choice-free).

  Purpose. The forcing spectrum σ(T) is meant to be an ABSOLUTE measure of how
  much non-constructive idealization a theorem costs. "Absolute" requires that
  the zero-point (the δ-forced base the cost is measured above) is not an
  arbitrary encoding but is FORCED up to unique isomorphism. This file proves,
  in Lean, that the base carrier `DistinctionNat` (ℕδ) is a Lawvere natural-number
  object: the INITIAL δ-algebra, categorical among Peano models, with a UNIQUE
  isomorphism to any such model. ℤδ (`PRCInt`) and ℚδ (`PRCRat`) are built on it.

  STATUS (soul.mdc): the three carrier targets below are THEOREM, choice-free
  (`#print axioms` audits at the bottom; `Bijective` is kept Prop-valued precisely
  so `Equiv.ofBijective`/`invFun` do not route through `Classical.choice`).

  SCOPE — read this before over-claiming (director panel, 2026-07-04). Carrier
  rigidity is NECESSARY but NOT SUFFICIENT for "σ is absolute", and it is here
  BANKED, not treated as the headline. Two hard facts the panel established:

  * `DistinctionNat` is provably equivalent to `Nat`, so these theorems are a
    choice-free transport of the standard "ℕ is an NNO". The novelty is not the
    carrier theorem; it is what it unblocks.
  * The forcing spectrum over a FIXED posit alphabet {EM,LPO,MP} is provably NOT
    absolute: e.g. σ_{EM,LPO,MP}(LLPO) = {LPO} while HA+LLPO ⊬ LPO, so the
    fixed-alphabet ledger OVERSTATES strength. No carrier theorem repairs this.
    Absoluteness must be relocated to a UNIVERSAL PROPERTY on the proof-system
    side (an initial/free posit-grading valued in intrinsic degrees — the σ-analog
